eserves the transcript\nbut erases the boundaries between capture invocations.\n\nThe model should distinguish:\n\n- **capture turn:** a stop-hook capture observation with new transcript records\n  and a repository environment snapshot\n- **provider turn:** a provider-native conversation grouping, such as a user\n  prompt and the resulting assistant/tool activity\n\nCapture turns are the durable a\n[TRUNCATED]\ntion work is split across write and read time:\n\n- **Capture time:** write observations and deterministic index memberships from\n  the current turn snapshot, such as observed branch names, review ids, and\n  change ids.\n- **Read time:** answer association questions by looking up candidate turns from\n  indexes, reading their observations, and scoring/explaining likely related\n  sessions with the current heuristic version.\n\nCapture should not write final inferred relationships such as \"this PR is\nassociated with this session\" or \"this branch was produced by this session.\"\nIt only writes the facts and lookup entries needed to answer those questions\nefficiently later.\n\nThe index is not the association. It is a disposable acceleration structure.\nIf the heuristic changes, rebuild the index and old sessions can benefit\nretroactively.\n\nFor v1, write only branch, review, and change indexes:\n\n```text\ngitbutler:agentlog-index-version = 1\ngitbutler:agentlog-index:v1:branch:<branch-key> = set<session-key/turn-key>\ngitbutler:agentlog-index:v1:review:<review-key> = set<session-key/turn-key>\ngitbutler:agentlog-index:v1:change:<change-id> = set<session-key/turn-key>\n```\n\nThe index value includes both the session key and turn key so an index lookup can\nresolve directly to the owning session without scanning session turn lists.\nBranch and review index key material should be safe for GitMeta keys; hashing\nbranch/review values is acceptable as long as the readable values remain in the\nturn snapshot. Change ids are already compact, durable identifiers and can be\nused directly unless the GitMeta key rules require escaping.\n\nDo not write a path index in v1. Path-level keys can explode with large commits,\nbroad worktree changes, generated files, or dependency lockfile churn. File\npaths remain in the turn observations for scoring after branch/review/change\ncandidate discovery.\n\nIndex entries are candidate discovery only. Readers must verify candidates by\nloading the referenced turn detail and checking that the queried branch, review,\n","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-20T02:18:46.971Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"function_call_output","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]"}}}